author: Inside Edition
description: There's growing controversy over President Donald Trump's treatment of a reporter aboard Air Force One. Trump called a female reporter "Piggy" as she was asking him questions about the Epstein files. The president answered her first question, but when she tried to ask a follow-up, he lashed out. A photograph of the moment shows Trump thrusting his finger in the reporter's face. She is Cathrine Lucey from Bloomberg News.
title: President Donald Trump Tells Female Reporter 'Quiet, Piggy'

author: Inside Edition
description: Andrew, 9, Alexander, 7, and Tanner, 5. had been on a Thanksgiving visitation in 2010 with their dad, but when they were to return to their mother, they were missing. Their mother called the police. John Skelton told cops he gave his sons to a mysterious "underground organization." Despite a massive search, the brothers were never found. Skelton was sentenced to 15 years in prison for unlawful imprisonment. He was due to be released next week, but now he's been charged with murdering his sons.
title: Father Of 3 Boys Who Went Missing In 2010 Faces Murder Charges

author: Inside Edition
description: Robyn Polston, 43, is being accused of having an affair with her daughter's 14-year-old boyfriend. The mother's former in-laws, Brendan Polston and Kira Grove, spoke with Inside Edition. Robyn first met the teenage boy in May 2023. Grove says last year she learned that Robyn, who used to be married to her brother, was pregnant. Cops say a DNA test proved the teen boy was their father and took Robyn into custody, charging her with criminal sexual assault and possession of child pornography.
title: Woman Charged After Allegedly Conceiving Child With 14-Year-Old Boy

author: Inside Edition
description: A controversial new app called "2Wai" allows you to recreate dead loved ones so that generation after generation can keep in touch with their dead relatives. To create a digital family member, you record 3 minutes of video while they are still alive. The AI app copies their image, mannerisms and voice. The concept is the brainchild of former Disney star Calum Worthy. The app is being blasted on social media, but 2Wai claims so many people are using the site, their servers can't cope.
title: Mixed Reactions To '2wai,' App That Recreates Dead Loved Ones

author: Inside Edition
description: Famed 90s fitness icon Susan Powter was once an electric personality whipping America into shape. But in 1995, she shocked her fans and declared bankruptcy. Her multi-million-dollar weight loss empire was gone. Now at 67, she lives in Las Vegas delivering food for Uber Eats and struggles to find the healthy food she once promoted. Powter says her financial ruin came after getting bad financial advice. Powter shares her story in the new documentary "Stop the Insanity: Finding Susan Powter."
title: 90s Fitness Icon Susan Powter Details Her Downfall In New Documentary

author: Inside Edition
description: Customs and border patrol agents are targeting Charlotte, North Carolina, in an operation dubbed "Charlotte's Web." Cellphone video captured several arrests in the southern city over the weekend. In one incident, agents broke the truck window of an American citizen named Willy Aceituno. Aceituno, who told reporters he was injured in the action, was detained but later released. Protests against the ICE surge were also evident in uptown Charlotte.
title: ICE Surges Into North Carolina With 'Charlotte's Web'

author: Inside Edition
description: According to the FBI, overseas scammers are misusing bitcoin ATMs to target senior citizens across the country. After getting them on the phone, scammers con the elderly into sending them thousands of dollars via these machines. INSIDE EDITION spoke with two elderly women from opposite sides of the country who both fell victim to this new scam. One got all her money back, but police say the other will never recover her $11,000.
title: Scammers Misuse Bitcoin ATMs To Trick Seniors Into Sending Them Money

author: Inside Edition
description: When Yugoslavia collapsed into civil war in the early 1990s, the city of Sarajevo was caught in the crossfire – literally. Bosnian Serb forces mounted repeated attacks on the population there, killing an estimated 11,000 civilians. Some of those civilians may have been killed by foreign nationals, from Italy and other European countries, who paid to be part of "sniper safaris." These "sniper tourists" are alleged to have joined Bosnian Serb forces in targeting people on the streets.
title: Did 'Sniper Tourists' Pay To Shoot Civilians During Siege Of Sarajevo?

author: Inside Edition
description: In 2000 when Hilton was 19, she was apparently spotted by Maxwell at a party during fashion week in New York. Now, Hilton says she has no recollection of that night.
title: Was Paris Hilton Targeted By Ghislaine Maxwell? #shorts

author: Inside Edition
description: You never want to end up in the emergency room—but are there secrets that can make visiting the ER an easier experience? INSIDE EDITION got the inside scoop from former New York E.R. Nurse Katie Duke. She advises potential patients that E.R.s always focus on life-or-death cases first, so a non-life-threatening problem could lead to you to wait a while. And she says to be careful with how many people you bring – those tight halls can get packed pretty quick.
title: Do You Know These Secrets Of The E.R.?

author: Inside Edition
description: Cops say filming content is not an excuse to hold up traffic. YouTuber Jack Doherty, 22, was placing an online bet when Miami Beach Police told him to step out of the street and onto a sidewalk. His plea for police patience was denied, and he was placed under arrest. Someone working with him caught the whole thing on video. Inside Edition Digital’s Mara Montalbano has more.
title: YouTuber Jack Doherty Arrested While Filming Content On Miami Street

author: Inside Edition
description: Eighteen players from Alabama's University of Montevallo women's soccer team got stuck in the elevator during a tournament in Huntsville. It got so warm in the elevator that several players took off their uniforms to stay cool. Help arrived in the form of the local fire department who were able to pry the elevator doors open and the players started streaming out. They went on to beat the opposing team.
title: Entire Collegiate Soccer Team Stuck In Elevator During Tournament
